<body>
	<div class="banner">
		<center><font color="white" size="16px" face="arial">SirA</font></center>
	</div>
	<div align="center" class="main-content">
		<div class="spacer">
	</div><br>			<label class="collapse_ACT" for="_1"><font size="5px">SirA transcriptional activity</font></label>
				<input id="_1" type="checkbox">
				<div class="ACT"><br><ul><li>Although SirA does not regulate csrA , this gene was also under crp/cya control .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16949866" target="_blank">16949866</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , SirA activates hilD expression post-transcriptionally .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22021388" target="_blank">22021388</a>]<br></li>
				<label class="ACT_collapse_similarity" for="act_similarity_3">
Thus SirA induction of csrBC prevents CsrA action , indirectly activating hilD expression post-transcriptionally [ 43 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17208038" target="_blank">17208038</a>]<br></label>
<input id="act_similarity_3", type="checkbox">
<div class="ACT_similar">
<li>Thus , SirA induction of csrBC prevents CsrA action , indirectly activating hilD expression posttranscriptionally ( 17 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18245288" target="_blank">18245288</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , SirA induction of csrBC prevents CsrA action , indirectly activating hilD expression posttranscriptionally .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18723621" target="_blank">18723621</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>Second , SirA could be activated by overexpression per se if activation involves a concentration-sensitive step , such as SirA oligomer formation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10672185" target="_blank">10672185</a>]<br></li>
<li>S1 represents activation by HilD and S2 represents activation by SirA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19537165" target="_blank">19537165</a>]<br></li>
<li>SirA specifically binds to csrC but not to hilD , hilA , hilC or ssrAB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21518393" target="_blank">21518393</a>]<br></li>
<li>Because sirC expression does not require HilA , we sought to determine whether SirC , like SirA , acts to regulate hilA expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10322010" target="_blank">10322010</a>]<br></li>
<li>Moreover , previous studies indicate that SirA , CsrB/CsrC , CsrA and HilD are required by Salmonella to display phenotypic features involved in intestinal infection ( Jones , 2005 ; Altier , 2005 ; Lucchetti-Miganeh et al. , 2008 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21518393" target="_blank">21518393</a>]<br></li>
<li>The two-component regulator PhoP/Q , which is mainly responsive to magnesium cation ( Garcia-Vescovi et al. , 1996 ; Groisman , 1998 ) , represses hilA , whereas SirA , a member of the phosphorylated response-regulator protein family , positively affects hilA ( Behlau and Miller , 1993 ; Johnston et al. , 1996 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10672185" target="_blank">10672185</a>]<br></li>
<li>Alternatively , acetyl-phosphate seems to directly phosphorylate the response-regulator SirA or the sensor kinase BarA ( Altier et al. , 2000b ; Lawhon et al. , 2002 ; Teplitski et al. , 2003 ; 2006 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21518393" target="_blank">21518393</a>]<br></li>
<li>SirA is a response-regulator of the FixJ family that is phosphorylated by the tri-partite histidine sensor kinase , BarA ( Nagasawa et al. , 1992 ; Pernestig et al. , 2001 ; Teplitski et al. , 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16949866" target="_blank">16949866</a>]<br></li>
<li>The SirA protein is phosphorylated by the histidine sensor kinase BarA and potentially via ackA and pta from the cellular pool of low-molecular-weight phosphate donors ( Lawhon et al. , 2002 ; Pernestig et al. , 2001 ; Teplitski et al. , 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16949866" target="_blank">16949866</a>]<br></li>
<li>Positive regulators include BarA/SirA , FliZ , EnvZ/OmpR , FadD , CsrB , HilD and some nucleoid binding proteins ( Fis , HU ) , while Pag , HilE , Ams and the nucleoid binding proteins Hha and H-NS are negatively regulating hilA transcription ( Altier et al. 2000a , b Fahlen et al. 2000 ; Lucas et al. 2000 ; Wilson et al. 2001 ; Schechter et al. 2003 ; Baxter et al. 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18563621" target="_blank">18563621</a>]<br></li>
<li>In both E. coli and Salmonella , BarA autophosphorylates in response to an unknown signal , and then trans-phosphorylates SirA ( Pernestig et al. , 2001 ; Teplitski et al. , 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16949866" target="_blank">16949866</a>]<br></li>
<li>Once phosphorylated , SirA directly binds the hilA and hilC promoters and contributes to Salmonella enteropathogenesis in a bovine model ( Ahmer et al. , 1999a ; Teplitski et al. , 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16949866" target="_blank">16949866</a>]<br></li>
<li>The global response-regulator , SirA , positively regulates the expression of hilA , hilC , and hilD encoded within SPI-1 and SPI-2 ( Teplitski et al. 2006 ; Martínez et al. 2011 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24500522" target="_blank">24500522</a>]<br></li>
<li>This is consistent with previous studies indicating that SirA orthologs regulate gene expression through the corresponding CsrB and CsrC orthologs ( Babitzke and Romeo , 2007 ; Lucchetti-Miganeh et al. , 2008 ; Brencic et al. , 2009 ; Timmermans and Van Melderen , 2010 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21518393" target="_blank">21518393</a>]<br></li>
<li>SirA regulates hilA and is required for invasion gene expression and enteropathogenesis ( Ahmer et al. , 1999 ; Altier et al. , 2000a ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12453229" target="_blank">12453229</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast , csrC was bound by MBP-SirA , starting at a concentration of 2 µM ( Fig. 4E ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21518393" target="_blank">21518393</a>]<br></li>
<li>SirA regulates csrC expression both directly and indirectly .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24187088" target="_blank">24187088</a>]<br></li>
<li>SirA then activates both csrB and csrC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16368988" target="_blank">16368988</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , SirA activates both csrB and csrC , which prevent CsrA action and preserve HilD activity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23554419" target="_blank">23554419</a>]<br></li>
<li>PCR-ampliﬁed and puriﬁed fragments csrB-370 , csrB-230 , csrB-170 , csrB-114 , csrB-370R1 * , and csrB-370R2 * were incubated with increasing concentrations ( 0 to 3 M ) of puriﬁed and phosphorylated MBP-SirA fusion protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24187088" target="_blank">24187088</a>]<br></li>
<li>As could be expected , MBP-SirA bound to the csrC-350 and csrC-239 fragments ( Fig. 6C and F ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24187088" target="_blank">24187088</a>]<br></li>
<li>PCR-ampliﬁed and puriﬁed fragments csrC-350 , csrC-350R1 * , csrC-350R2 * , csrC-239 , and csrC-119 were incubated with increasing concentrations ( 0 to 3 M ) of puriﬁed and phosphorylated MBP-SirA fusion protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24187088" target="_blank">24187088</a>]<br></li>
<li>Growth conditions and reporter assays Previously , we have shown that maximal effects of SirA are observed while cells are actively chemotaxing through motility agar ( Goodier and Ahmer , 2001 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16949866" target="_blank">16949866</a>]<br></li>
<li>The sensor kinase BarA and its cognate regulator SirA are involved in carbohydrate metabolism , motility , bioﬁlm formation , and invasion ( 227 , 264 -- 267 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23554419" target="_blank">23554419</a>]<br></li>
<li>Model 5 In this model , SirA regulates HilD , which in turn regulates HilC , RtsA and HilA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19537165" target="_blank">19537165</a>]<br></li>
<li>Puriﬁed BarA198 can autophosphorylate and transfer phosphate to SirA in vitro .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14645287" target="_blank">14645287</a>]<br></li>
<li>In scenario-3 , SirA is considered to activate HilA and HilC , with HilD as a co-activator .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19537165" target="_blank">19537165</a>]<br></li>
<li>TTSS gene transcription is activated in response to environmental signals and requires transcriptional-regulators encoded within ( HilA ) and outside ( SirA ) SPI1 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10322010" target="_blank">10322010</a>]<br></li>
<li>sirC is carried within SPI1 , and like other SPI1 genes , its expression is regulated by several regulators ( PhoP , SirA , and SirB ) and in response to growth-phase .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10322010" target="_blank">10322010</a>]<br></li>
<li>SirA ( indirectly via the CsrABC system [ 2 ] ) also activates SPI1 but represses ﬂhDC ( 26 , 61 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17951383" target="_blank">17951383</a>]<br></li>
<li>At higher concentrations ( ≥ 5 µM ) , phosphorylated or nonphosphorylated MBP-SirA bound to all of these fragments , including sigD , suggesting that MBP-SirA binds nonspecifically at these concentrations ( data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21518393" target="_blank">21518393</a>]<br></li>
<li>The activation of csrB by SirA is likely to be direct , as SirA has been shown to-bind to csrB DNA ( 34 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16368988" target="_blank">16368988</a>]<br></li>
<li>The addition of SirA-His to a BarA198 autophosphoryla-6 tion reaction allowed BarA198 to transfer phosphate to SirA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14645287" target="_blank">14645287</a>]<br></li>
<li>The pool of phosphorylated SirA appeared to be stable for at least 30 min .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14645287" target="_blank">14645287</a>]<br></li>
<li>The concentration of phosphorylated SirA required to shift each of these promoters was determined to be approximately 600 nM .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14645287" target="_blank">14645287</a>]<br></li>
<li>The possible presence of a direct interaction of SirA with their respective promoters remains to be demonstrated .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23554419" target="_blank">23554419</a>]<br></li>
<li>This ensures that SirA is available to be phosphorylated by BarA in response to an as yet unknown signal .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16949866" target="_blank">16949866</a>]<br></li>
<li>Discussion In our previous work , we have proposed that BarA , a sensor kinase , and SirA , a response-regulator , constitute a two-component regulator that induces the expression of SPI-1 genes in response to an unidentiﬁed extracellular signal .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12453229" target="_blank">12453229</a>]<br></li>
<li>Currently , it is known that acetate , when converted to acetylphosphate , increases SPI1 gene expression through activation of the sensor kinase/response-regulator system BarA / SirA ( 22 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16391141" target="_blank">16391141</a>]<br></li>
<li>Much of our genetic data points to SirA as the likely cognate response-regulator for BarA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=10672185" target="_blank">10672185</a>]<br></li>
<li>For example , the response-regulator SirA has been shown to activate hilA transcription in the presence of suitable environmental signals ( 79 , SO ) , providing us with tools for both an on - ( S i r M i l A ) and off-switch ( PhoPmediated prg response ) for invasion .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11370771" target="_blank">11370771</a>]<br></li>
<li>In response to salt , the sensor kinase BarA autophosphorylates and donates its phosphoryl group to its cognate response-regulator , SirA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18441068" target="_blank">18441068</a>]<br></li>
<li>Acetyl-phosphate phosphorylates either the response-regulator , SirA , directly or the sensor kinase , BarA , which in turn transfers its phosphate groups to SirA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12453229" target="_blank">12453229</a>]<br></li>
<li>BarA is a sensor kinase that responds to an unknown signal by phosphorylating the response-regulator SirA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16949866" target="_blank">16949866</a>]<br></li>
<li>BarA is believed to activate the transcriptional-regulator SirA in response to an unknown environmental signal .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11292791" target="_blank">11292791</a>]<br></li>
<li>BarA is a sensor kinase , which phosphorylates the response-regulator SirA in response to extracellular signals .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=27920756" target="_blank">27920756</a>]<br></li>
<li>SirA phosphorylation in vivo seems to be critical for its function , since when its predicted phosphorylated residue , Asp54 , is substituted for an alanine , or in the absence of its cognate sensor kinase BarA , csrB expression is not induced ( data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21518393" target="_blank">21518393</a>]<br></li>
<li>Within the intestinal tract of an animal host , BarA/SirA is activated , either in response to high concentrations of acetate or by an as-yet-unidentiﬁed signal for BarA activation ( 24 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16368988" target="_blank">16368988</a>]<br></li>
<li>SirA is activated either by the sensor kinase BarA or independently of BarA by acetate .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16368988" target="_blank">16368988</a>]<br></li>
<li>SirA does not regulate crp or cya Since crp/cya are required for sirA expression , we examined the relationship in the opposite direction by testing the hypothesis that sirA regulates crp or cya .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16949866" target="_blank">16949866</a>]<br></li>
<li>Surprisingly , despite the very strong regulation seen with fusions , the csrC promoter was not directly bound by SirA in vitro ( Fig. 4B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16949866" target="_blank">16949866</a>]<br></li>
<li>Consistent with these results , phosphorylated SirA was found to directly bind the csrB promoter but not the csrA promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14645287" target="_blank">14645287</a>]<br></li>
<li>SirA does not regulate the csrA gene or bind the csrA promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14645287" target="_blank">14645287</a>]<br></li>
<li>As expected , the genes regulated by SirA are also under catabolite control .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16949866" target="_blank">16949866</a>]<br></li>
<li>SirA is required for both repression by bile and activation by acetate ( 41 , 56 ) , but the pathways for responses to other signals have not been deﬁned .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18424519" target="_blank">18424519</a>]<br></li>
<li>FIG 3 SirA regulates csrB by binding to the IR sequence .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24187088" target="_blank">24187088</a>]<br></li>
<li>These DNA fragments correspond to those contained in the hilD-cat , hilA-cat , hilC-cat , ssrAB-cat and csrC-cat transcriptional fusions , which were regulated by SirA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21518393" target="_blank">21518393</a>]<br></li>
<li>SirA activates the virulence gene sopB in motility agar .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11244064" target="_blank">11244064</a>]<br></li>
<li>It was previously shown that the maximal effects of SirA are observed when cells are actively involved in chemotaxis through motility agar ( 24 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14645287" target="_blank">14645287</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , SirA directly activates csrB , which antagonizes the activity of CsrA , which is known to directly affect ﬂhDC ( Fig. 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14645287" target="_blank">14645287</a>]<br></li>
<li>In S. enterica serovar Typhimurium , SirA was found to repress all levels of the ﬂagellar regulon while activating vi-rulence gene expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11244064" target="_blank">11244064</a>]<br></li>
<li>In S. enterica serovar Typhi-murium , SirA positively regulates the invasion of tissue culture * Corresponding author .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14645287" target="_blank">14645287</a>]<br></li>
<li>BarA198 was auto-phosphorylated in the presence of 1.5 mM ATP at room temperature for 15 min , and then used to trans-phosphorylate SirA for 15 min as described previously ( Teplitski et al. , 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16949866" target="_blank">16949866</a>]<br></li>
<li>SirA regulates csrC In both Salmonella and E. coli , SirA directly regulates csrB , a gene encoding a small regulatory RNA that inhibits-the-activity of the RNA-binding protein CsrA ( Suzuki et al. , 2002 ; Teplitski et al. , 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16949866" target="_blank">16949866</a>]<br></li>
<li>SirA , when activated , positively regulates the transcription of hilA and hilC , that serves as an initial effector of bacterial invasion pathway ( Johnston et al. , 1996 ; Teplitski et al. , 2006 ) ; therefore the induction of sirA in Salmonella leads to bacterial association and bioﬁlm formation ( Salazar et al. , 2013 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=27565525" target="_blank">27565525</a>]<br></li>
<li>SirA activates expression of the CsrB and CsrC RNAs , which antagonize the action of CsrA ( Romeo 1998 ; Weilbacher et al. 2003 ; Fortune et al. 2006 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22021388" target="_blank">22021388</a>]<br></li>
<li>The transcription of csrB , but not of csrA , is under control of the BarA/SirA orthologs of Escherichia and Salmonella ( Suzuki et al. , 2002 ; Teplitski et al. , 2003 ; Weilbacher et al. , 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16949866" target="_blank">16949866</a>]<br></li>
<li>However while SirA inhibits CsrA activity via the activation of csrB , SirA does not regulate the transcription of csrA ( Suzuki et al. , 2002 ; Teplitski et al. , 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16949866" target="_blank">16949866</a>]<br></li>
<li>An evolutionarily conserved function of SirA appears to be the direct activation of csrB ( carbon storage regulator ) , an RNA that antagonizes the activity of the RNA-binding protein CsrA ( Suzuki et al. , 2002 ; Teplitski et al. , 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15130116" target="_blank">15130116</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of barA , SirA can be phosphorylated from the cellular pool of low-molecular-weight phosphate donors ( Lawhon et al. , 2002 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16949866" target="_blank">16949866</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although BarA is believed to be the cognate sensor of the regulator SirA ( Altier et al. , 2000a ; Johnston et al. , 1996 ) , we postulate that CpxA is also a fairly probable candidate for the partner sensor of SirA , especially at pH 6 ?	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14523114" target="_blank">14523114</a>]<br></li>
<li>This regulatory cascade is under the influence of catabolite repression , through the positive control of SirA expression exerted by the cAMP receptor protein CRP ( Teplitski et al. , 2006 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21518393" target="_blank">21518393</a>]<br></li>
<li>The regulatory cascade can also be activated by short-chain fatty acids , such as acetate , formate and propionate , which stimulate the sensor kinase activity of BarA , and thus phosphorylation of SirA orthologs ( Chavez et al. , 2010 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21518393" target="_blank">21518393</a>]<br></li>
<li>BarA/SirA regulatory system located at the top of invasion cascade is activated by environmental signals , responsible for motility , virulence , and survival ( Prouty and Gunn 2000 ; Teplitski et al. 2006 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=24500522" target="_blank">24500522</a>]<br></li>
<li>In Salmonella , the presence of bile salts seems to affect BarA-SirA dependent responses ( Prouty and Gunn , 2000 ) and results from another study have shown that short chain fatty acids affect CsrA mediated phenotypes in a pathway involving SirA , but probably not BarA ( Lawhon et al. , 2002 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19919539" target="_blank">19919539</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , although SirA has been shown to be required for Salmonella intracellular replication ( Chan et al. , 2005 ) , this does not seem to be related to the SirA-mediated regulation of the SPI-2 genes intracellularly , but instead of other target genes , in agreement with its global regulatory nature observed in Salmonella and other bacteria ( Ahmer et al. , 1999 , Goodier and Ahmer , 2001 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21518393" target="_blank">21518393</a>]<br></li>
<li>International Journal of Medical Microbiology 296 ( 2006 ) 449 -- 466 www.elsevier.de/ijmm Catabolite repression of the SirA regulatory cascade in Salmonella enterica Max Teplitski , Robert I. Goodier , Brian M.M. Ahmer a , b ,1 b a Department of Soil and Water Science , Institute of Food and Agricultural Sciences , University of Florida , Gainesville , FL 32611-0290 , USA b Department of Microbiology , Ohio State University , 484 West 12th Avenue , Columbus , OH 43210-1292 , USA Received 6 September 2005 ; received in revised form 21 June 2006 ; accepted 21 June 2006 Abstract Orthologs of the Salmonella BarA/SirA two-component system are required for virulence , motility , secondary metabolism and stress survival throughout the g-proteobacteria .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16949866" target="_blank">16949866</a>]<br></li>
